observations.recommendation:
2.11	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require:
(1) 	the inventory committee to conduct inventory of local roads under the jurisdiction of the municipality and prepare the necessary Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System (RPCRNS) using the form in Annex C of COA Circular 2015-008. The RPCRNS should be reconciled with the Accounting and GSO records;
(2)	The Municipal Engineer to provide the Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and segregation of road components for those with data on construction cost. For those not posted in the registry but without identified cost and those included in the RPCRNS but not in the registry, the fair value must be used in determining the cost of road components and thereafter shall provide the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
(3)	the Municipal Accountant to depreciate the carrying amount of existing roads and its components to reflect the asset in its used condition and accordingly adjust the amount recorded in the Road Network account supported by the RPCRNS, Registry Infrastructure for Roads and working paper on the determination of the depreciated replacement cost per registry. Subsequently, at the end of each year, a lapsing schedule for the computation of depreciation for each depreciable road component must be prepared as basis for recording depreciation expenses and the required Local Road Network Ledger Card for each road network shall likewise be maintained; and
(4)	the MGSO at the end or every accounting period to render a Report on Local Road Network using the pro-forma schedule in Annex A of the same Circular and maintain local road inventory, Road Map and complete Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components.

16.12	We recommended that the Local School Board, being the one responsible in the formulation, approval, and utilization of the SEF Budget as provided under RA No. 7160 or the Local Government Code:
(1) exert earnest efforts in ensuring that all budgeted projects, programs and activities are optimally and fully implemented;
(2) remind all beneficiary schools as to the status of utilization and availability of their respective budgets;
(3) revisit the revised guidelines on the use of SEF under DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 to ensure a more strategic and efficient formulation and utilization of resources for priority programs and projects; and
(4) consider realignment of funds to other priority programs, projects and activities, if warranted by circumstances.

We recommended that management:

undertake a complete periodic physical inventory of municipal properties and immediately reconcile the balances of any affected accounts to permit fair presentation of PPE in the financial statements;

prioritize attendance of municipal personnel involved in preparing Inventory Reports of PPE on Seminars on Property and Supply Management System, should there be one, to further increase their knowledge in relation to their assigned tasks;

safeguard municipal properties from possible loss or deterioration by ensuring that movable PPEs are kept inside Office premises, except in meritorious instances where movable PPEs may be temporarily kept at home for purposes of making reports or incidental to the discharge of official functions; and

maintain Stock and Property Cards, through the MGSO, to properly account the receipt and disposition of PPE items.

We recommended that the Local School Board, being the one responsible in the formulation, approval, and utilization of the SEF Budget as provided under RA No. 7160 or the Local Government Code:

(1) exert earnest efforts in ensuring that all budgeted projects, programs and activities are optimally and fully implemented;

(2) remind all beneficiary schools as to the status of utilization and availability of their respective budgets;

(3) revisit the revised guidelines on the use of SEF under DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 to ensure a more strategic and efficient formulation and utilization of resources for priority programs and projects; and

(4) consider realignment of funds to other priority programs, projects and activities, if warranted by circumstances.
